body:
I'd assumed that although there are different ways of creating components, the results would be the same and we'd be able to find them in the document in a uniform manner. When I try and use the test utility method `scryRenderedComponentsWithType`, it can't find components created using a pure function.

```
const Wrapper = React.createClass({
      render() {
          return <div>{this.props.children}</div>
      }
});

const ErrorMessage = React.createClass({
      render() {
          return (
              <div className="alert alert-danger">
                  <div>{this.props.error.toString()}</div>
              </div>
          );
      },
  });

const ErrorMessagePureFunction = ({ error }) => (
        <div className="alert alert-danger">
            <div>{error.toString()}</div>
        </div>
);

describe('when rendering pure function components', () => {
        it('should be able to find in the document', () => {
            const output = Utils.renderIntoDocument(<Wrapper><ErrorMessage error={new Error('whoops')} /></Wrapper>);
            expect(Utils.scryRenderedComponentsWithType(output, ErrorMessage).length).toBe(1); // succeeds

            const outputWithPureFunction = Utils.renderIntoDocument(<Wrapper><ErrorMessagePureFunction error={new Error('whoops')} /></Wrapper>);
            expect(Utils.scryRenderedComponentsWithType(outputWithPureFunction, ErrorMessagePureFunction).length).toBe(1); // fails
        });
});
```

Should this test pass or is there another way of getting pure function components in the document?
